1. Purpose of This Document

This document maps key risks in Veriflow’s AI credit scoring system against:

ISO/IEC 27001
NIST Cybersecurity Framework
ISO/IEC 42001
ENISA (AI-specific threat considerations)

The objective is not to demonstrate compliance.
It is to show where existing control frameworks are sufficient, and where they are not.

In practice, most control failures occur at those boundaries.

2. Framing Observation (Before the Table)

There is a tendency to assume that if a system is secure, it is therefore safe to deploy.

That assumption does not hold for AI systems.

A credit scoring model can be:

Secure (no breach, no unauthorised access), and
Functionally operational

…and still produce outcomes that are:

Unfair
Unexplainable
Misaligned with regulatory expectations

Or simply wrong in a way that is hard to detect until damage has already occurred.

Traditional frameworks were not designed to answer those questions.

3. Control Mapping
3.1 Training Data Integrity & Confidentiality

Risk
Training data is exposed, altered, or sourced in a way that introduces hidden bias or error.

Primary framework anchor
ISO 27001 / NIST CSF

Where that is sufficient

Encryption at rest and in transit
Access controls
Supplier assurance (Databridge)

Where it is not sufficient
These controls confirm the data is protected — not that it is appropriate.

A dataset can be perfectly secured and still unsuitable for model training.

Additional governance expectation (ISO 42001)

Documented data provenance
Assessment of representativeness
Explicit acceptance of known limitations

ENISA-informed consideration

Data poisoning risk (malicious or accidental)
Dependency on third-party data pipelines
3.2 Model Decision Transparency (Explainability)

Risk
The organisation cannot adequately explain why a customer was declined credit.

Primary framework anchor
ISO 42001

Where traditional frameworks fall short
ISO 27001 confirms the system is controlled.
It does not require the system to be understandable.

Control expectation

Model documentation (model card or equivalent)
Defined explanation standards for adverse decisions
Internal ability to reconstruct decision logic when challenged

There is a practical limit here — not all models are fully explainable.
The risk is pretending they are.

3.3 Human Oversight & Intervention

Risk
Decisions are made without meaningful human review, particularly in borderline or high-impact cases.

Primary framework anchor
ISO 42001

Where traditional frameworks fall short
NIST CSF introduces governance concepts, but does not define what “appropriate human oversight” looks like in practice.

Control expectation

Defined escalation thresholds
Clear ownership of override decisions
Evidence that intervention is possible (not just documented)

In many organisations, “human in the loop” exists on paper but not in workflow.

3.4 Model Drift & Performance Degradation

Risk
Model performance deteriorates over time due to changes in customer behaviour, economic conditions, or data inputs.

Primary framework anchor
ISO 42001

Where traditional frameworks fall short
ISO 27001 treats systems as relatively stable assets.
AI systems are not stable — they degrade.

Control expectation

Ongoing performance monitoring
Defined thresholds for retraining or suspension
Periodic validation against current data

A model that was valid six months ago may no longer be valid today.
This is rarely treated with the urgency it deserves.

3.5 Incident Response (AI-Specific)

Risk
The model causes harm (e.g. systemic unfair decisions), but this is not recognised or treated as an incident.

Primary framework anchor
NIST CSF + ISO 42001

Where traditional frameworks fall short
Incident response is usually triggered by security events, not decision failures.

Control expectation

Definition of what constitutes an “AI incident”
Integration with existing incident response processes
Clear escalation path to governance / compliance functions

Not every failure will look like a breach.
Some will look like a pattern.

3.6 Third-Party AI Dependencies (Databridge Analytics Ltd)

Risk
Reliance on third-party data or models introduces risk outside direct organisational control.

Primary framework anchor
ISO 27001 / NIST CSF

Where that is sufficient

Supplier due diligence
Contractual controls
Security assurance

Where it is not sufficient
These controls assess the vendor’s security posture, not the downstream impact of their data on model behaviour.

Additional governance expectation (ISO 42001)

Assessment of how third-party inputs affect outcomes
Defined fallback if vendor data becomes unreliable

ENISA-informed consideration

Supply chain manipulation
Hidden dependencies in data enrichment processes
3.7 AI-Specific Threat Considerations

Risk
The model is manipulated, exploited, or behaves unpredictably under adversarial conditions.

Primary reference
ENISA

Examples

Data poisoning (training data deliberately corrupted)
Model evasion (inputs crafted to bypass controls)
Model inversion (extracting sensitive data from outputs)

These risks are not theoretical.
They are simply not yet consistently integrated into standard control sets.

4. Key Takeaway

ISO 27001 and NIST CSF answer the question:

“Is the system secure and managed?”

ISO 42001 begins to answer:

“Is the system behaving in a way we can justify?”

ENISA material pushes further:

“How might this system be manipulated in ways we are not currently detecting?”

All three perspectives are required.

Relying on one creates blind spots.
Relying on all three still requires judgement.

5. Final Observation

Most governance failures will not occur because controls are absent.

They will occur because:

Controls were assumed to cover more than they actually do
Or because the boundary between frameworks was never examined

This document is intended to make those boundaries visible.
